<br>
But for now, all you really need is one link - <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.gamasutra.com">www.gamasutra.com</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->. Check it out. Once you sign up (for free), there are job listings, contract work, very helpful articles and a whole lot more. I swear I've seen ads for internships there now and again.<br>
<br>
Also, you might want to sign up on <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.monster.com">www.monster.com</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> and make a job search agent for all NE locations with the words &quot;game&quot; and &quot;intern&quot; in it. You will get many mails, but with a little effort you should be able to easily sort out the internships.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Edit add</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->: By the way, don't narrow your search too much by accepting only internships. I've spoken to a number of game development contacts and all of them have said the best way into the industry is to get a part-time job as a game tester.<br>
<br>
Lots of kids want this job because even though the pay stinks, you &quot;get to play games all day.&quot; This is true, but it's also a very effective way for the management to weed out the gamer doodz from the people serious about making a game and helping to make it better. The best way to show you're part of the second group is to take the job seriously and act professionally. Realize you are there not to play the game, but to test it and to give helpful feedback to make it better.<br>
<br>
They tell me doing well at this job opens many doors very quickly and gets you some initial contacts. I myself am not in a position to accept a $5 an hour part time job in hopes of making contacts, but this may be just what you need at this stage.<br>
<br>
Good luck and remember who helped you when you were a nobody. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://jens-smileys3.netfirms.com/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p>-Geln,<br>
